{{Infobox person | name = Jēkabs Bīne | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1895|4|11}} | birth_place = [[Riga]], [[Latvia]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1955|10|24|1895|4|11}} | death_place = [[Riga]], [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|Latvian SSR]] | nationality = Latvian | education = [[Art Academy of Latvia]] | home_town = | occupation = Artist | years_active = | spouse = }}
'''Jēkabs Bīne''' (11 April 1895-24 October 1955) was a Latvian painter, [[stained glass]] artist, teacher and art critic.
== Biography == Jēkabs Bīne was born in [[Riga]] in 1895 in merchant family. He studied at the [[Riga City Art School]] (1913-1915), [[Kharkov Art School]] (1915-1918) and the [[Art Academy of Latvia]] (1921–1926).<ref>[http://www.artnet.com/artists/jekabs-bine/biography Jekabs Bine Biography]. [[Artnet]].</ref> His graduation work from [[Jānis Tilbergs]]' figurative painting class at the Art Academy was the painting ''Resurrection''. He held teaching positions throughout his life: at the Art Studio of the Latvian People University (1928-1940), Riga People University, Institute of Housekeeping in Kaucminde (1932-1939), at the Riga State Art of Craft School (1933-1944), at the School of the Riga society of painters (1936-1939), at the Art Academy of Latvia (1942-1944), at the Kuldiga Secondary Art School (1944-1951), and at combine "Art" (1951-1955).<ref name="paintings">[http://paintings.lv/en/artist/55?view=about Jekabs Bine]. Galerija Jēkabs.</ref>
His first solo exhibition was held in 1917. In the 1920s he painted Christian subjects, including the altarpieces for the churches in Cesvaines (1924), Jumprava (1926) and Vecsaule (1927). His focus on sacral painting developed into an interest in Latvian mythology, [[idealism]] and an ambition to connect art to folk culture and nature.<ref name="paintings" /> He studied the symbols of Latvian ornamentation and incorporated this in his art. He became involved in [[Ernests Brastiņš]]' [[Modern Paganism|neopagan]] movement [[Dievturība]] and became one of its main public promotors.<ref name="opentheology">Anita Stasulane, Gatis Ozoliņš. [https://www.degruyter.com/downloadpdf/j/opth.2017.3.issue-1/opth-2017-0019/opth-2017-0019.pdf Transformations of Neopaganism in Latvia: From Survival to Revival]. ''[[Open Theology]]'' 2017; 3: 239–40.</ref>
From 1940 and throughout the [[Stalinist]] era this was repressed as "bourgeois art". Bīne's diaries show that he was disappointed with the direction of Soviet authorities set out for art and viewed it as vulgarization. He did however adapt to the new regime. As part of his acceptance of a position as a [[stained glass]] specialist in 1951, he wrote a 1952 paper titled ''Ornament'' in which he condemned his previous views on Latvian ornamentation.<ref name="opentheology" />
