'''''Northern River''''' is a 1914–15 [[oil painting]] by Canadian painter [[Tom Thomson]]. The work was inspired by a sketch completed over the same winter, possibly in [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]]. The completed canvas is large, measuring 115.1 × 102.0 cm (45<small>{{frac|5|16}}</small> × 40<small>{{frac|3|16}}</small> in). Painted over the winter of 1914–15, it was completed in Thomson's shack behind the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in [[Toronto]]. The painting was produced as he was entering the peak of his short art career and is considered one of his most notable works. In 1915 it was purchased by the [[National Gallery of Canada]] in [[Ottawa]] and has remained in the collection ever since.

==Background==
{{Further|Tom Thomson#Early recognition (1914–15)|Artistic development of Tom Thomson#Colour and experimentation (1914–15)}}
Thomson first visited [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]] in May 1912,<ref>{{plainlist|
* {{harvp|Hunter|2002|p=25}}
* {{harvp|Klages|2016|p=21}}
* {{harvp|Silcox|2006|p=20}}
* {{harvp|Stacey|2002|p=57}}}}</ref> venturing through the area on a canoe trip with his Grip colleague Ben Jackson.{{sfnp|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography#discovering-algonquin-park 10]}} Thomson's transition from commercial art towards his original style of painting began to be apparent around this time.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography#discovering-algonquin-park 10]}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=23}} His early works, such as ''Northern Lake'' (1912–13) and ''Evening'' (1913), were not outstanding technically, yet they did illustrate an above average ability regarding composition and colour handling.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/biography#thomsons-early-paintings 11]}}

''Northern River'' and the winter of 1914–15 stand as a point of transition in Thomson's art. In 1914 he made himself a sketch box to hold 8½ × 10½ inch (21.6 × 26.7&nbsp;cm) panels,{{sfnb|Davies|c. 1930}} allowing him greater opportunity for sketching.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=123}} [[A. Y. Jackson]] in particular taught him about the subtleties of composition, colour and technique in general,{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=123}} allowing the sketches that followed show a beginning desire to experiment with colour and texture rather than continue with the precision and subdued nature of his earlier works.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|pp=127, 133}}

==Description==

[[File:Tom Thomson The Pool.jpg|thumb|''The Pool'', Winter 1915–16. National Gallery of Canada, Ottawa]]

In a letter to [[James MacCallum]], Thomson referred to ''Northern River'' as his "swamp picture."{{sfnb|Thomson|1915}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/northern-river 26]}}{{sfnb|Murray|2004|p=110}}{{efn|group=note|Thomson would specifically write, {{quote|[...]

I hear that my swamp picture is down at [[Ottawa]] on appro. Hope they keep it.

Yours truly / Tom Thomson{{sfnb|Thomson|1915}}{{sfnb|Murray|2002|p=300}}}}}} Though Thomson was typically critical of his own work, he described the painting as being "not half bad" to a nephew.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=46}} [[David Milne (artist)|David Milne]], a Canadian artist and critic, praised the painting, writing in a letter,

{{quote|Just plain impossible, but he has done it, it stirs you. Any painter who has ever worked on this overlying pattern motive will realize at once that this is tackling a complication beyond reason. A great point in Thomson's favour this, and his lack of perfection. I am wary of craftsmanship. It is nothing in itself, neither emotion nor creation. [...] I rather think it would have been wiser to have taken your ten most prominent Canadians and sunk them in [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]]—and saved Tom Thomson.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/northern-river 26]}}{{sfnb|Milne|1932}}}}

In an article for ''[[Canadian Magazine]]'', MacCallumm would write about the uniqueness of the painting amongst Thomson's entire catalogue. In particular, while Thomson would normally depict trees as amalgamated masses, in this painting he gives them each an individual form: {{quote|Drawing was to [Thomson] the expression of form, and form might be expressed by any method, so long as the form is true. One would have expected that with his intimate knowledge of trees he would have loved to paint all their traceries. In the “Northern River” alone did he lavish detail on his trees and here only because it helped the pattern. In one in whom the sense of design, of decoration was so developed that is the more striking, for in his sketches and in his larger pictures he always treated trees as masses. In his painting of them he gives form structure and colour by dragging paint in bold strokes over an underlying tone. Like many other painters he felt the limitations of paint, the impossibility of expressing on a flat surface the solidity and thickness of a tree, and in some canvasses almost modeled them in paint, while in others he got the same effect by expressing them by deep grooves in the paint.{{sfnb|MacCallum|1918|pp=379–80}}}}

The painting recalls elements of A. Y. Jackson's 1914 canvas, ''A Frozen Lake'',{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=130}} which Thomson likely saw in November 1914 before Jackson took it in December to be exhibited.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|loc=p. 130 n. 107}} Both paintings share a motif of trees and thin, sinuous branches obscuring the view to a body of water.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=130}} The directional emphasis of the image is placed in the vertical direction, especially apparent when contrasted with the later canvas, ''The Pool''.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=70}}

Given Thomson's love of poetry,{{sfnb|Murray|1999|pp=viii, 12}} the title of the work may be a reference to the [[William Wilfred Campbell]] poem, ''A Northern River''. Campbell was a Canadian poet who lived in [[Owen Sound]], nearby to Thomson's hometown of [[Leith, Ontario|Leith]].{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=46}}

===Sketch to studio painting===
{{See also|Artistic development of Tom Thomson#Sketch to canvas}}

{{Infobox artwork
| image_file         = Thomson, Study for Northern River.jpg
| painting_alignment = 
| title              = Study for "Northern River"
| alt                = 
| artist             = Tom Thomson
| year               = Winter 1914–15
| medium             = [[Graphite]], brush and [[ink]] and [[gouache]] on [[Paperboard|illustration board]]
| catalogue          = 
| height_metric      = 30.0
| width_metric       = 26.7
| height_imperial    = 11<small>{{frac|13|16}}</small>
| width_imperial     = 10½
| metric_unit        = cm
| imperial_unit      = in
| city               = [[Toronto]]
| museum             = [[Art Gallery of Ontario]]
| accession          = 82/176
}}

It is not known where the original study was made. Though it is typically assumed to have been completed in Algonquin Park, Thomson's friend Winifred Trainor claimed that it was set outside the Park.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=46}} Curator Charles Hill has instead suggested that the sketch was "[p]robably painted in his Toronto studio, it is most likely a memory—an amalgam of experiences rather than a specific site."{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=130}}

The initial sketch of the scene illustrates Thomson's adept ability to transform his small sketches into powerful studio paintings.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=181–85}} This is apparent with other sketch-painting pairings, such as ''[[:File:Tom Thomson, Opulent October.jpg|Opulent October]]'', ''[[Spring Ice]]'', ''[[The Jack Pine]]'' and ''[[The West Wind (painting)|The West Wind]]'', amongst many other examples.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/northern-river 26]}} Thomson's first [[gouache]] study of the work was brightly coloured partly because gouache reflects more light than oil on canvas does. To make the eventual studio painting livelier, he included reds, oranges and yellows within the foreground, though still maintaining the original gouache blends in the sky.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/northern-river 26]}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=130}} The dominant colour of the painting is black, an oddity within Thomson's corpus.{{sfnb|Murray|2004|p=110}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=130}} Curator and scholar Joan Murray has written that the final canvas closely follows the original study, but with key differences. For one, the canvas is devoid of the accidental brushstrokes present in the sketch. Foreground space was also added to better convey depth and the trees are simpler and more defined, with less foliage present.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=46}}

===Art Nouveau===
{{see also|Art Nouveau}}
In Thomson's time as a commercial artist, he became familiar with the then contemporary decorative style of [[Art Nouveau]].{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=94, 210}}{{sfnb|Reid|2002|pp=65–83}} [[Art history|Art historian]] David P. Silcox has described ''Northern River'' as utilizing the same sinuous forms that are to be found in the art style.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/key-works/the-west-wind 47], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#commercial-art 71]}} Of particular note are the "S-curves" of the trees which have their origins in Thomson's work as a [[Drafter|draughtsman]].{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=60}} He would continue to utilize this motif in other later works, such as ''Decorative Landscape, Birches'' (1915–16) and ''The West Wind'' (1916–17).{{sfnb|Stacey|2002|p=59–60}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#diverse-influences 68], [https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#commercial-art 71]}} Fellow artist [[A. Y. Jackson]] would affirm the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]]'s tendency towards using Art Nouveau styles within their work, writing that, "We (the Group of Seven and Tom Thomson) treated our subjects with the freedom of designers. We tried to emphasize colour, line and pattern."{{sfnb|McKay|2011|p=185}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=[https://www.aci-iac.ca/art-books/tom-thomson/style-and-technique/#commercial-art 71]}}

